 the industry that fashion [companies] come to be interested in production =
and in costume.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><p st=
yle=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><strong>Jonathan, how did you link up w=
ith </strong><strong><em>Challengers</em></strong><strong> and
</strong><strong><em>Queer</em></strong><strong> director Luca Guadagnino, =
and how do you approach designing for film versus designing a ready-to-wear=
 collection?</strong></p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p=
><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;"><em>Jonathan Anderson</em>: I met=
 Luca maybe 10 years ago at a hotel in Milan. We were introduced by a P.R.,=
 and what was supposed to be a 30-minute coffee meeting ended up being a di=
nner that went on to the early hours, talking and
talking about art. And we=E2=80=99ve always been trying to figure out how t=
o work together. And when the pandemic happened, Luca approached me near th=
e end of it, and said, <em>Would you be up for doing costumes in a film? </=
em>And I think because of the pandemic, I was worried that I wasn=E2=80=99t=
 going to have a job. No one was buying luxury goods at that point. So I wa=
s like, <em>Sure, why not?</em> And about five weeks later, I was on a plan=
e to Boston to go and shoot this film. He=E2=80=99s like a dear friend. We
get on very well; he=E2=80=99s someone I speak with every day and whom I tr=
ust. Even in my own day job and in film, we have similar opinions on the wa=
y we see the world.</p><p style=3D"margin:0;margin-bottom:0px;">=C2=A0</p><=
p style=3D"margin:0;">Regarding how my approach differs=E2=80=94when I do a=
 fashion show, you have to tell a story in 15 minutes. We build a giant mau=
soleum for it, and then we tear it all down. It=E2=80=99s sort of this very=
 fast process, but at the same time, you=E2=80=99re trying to tell a story =
in each
season. For me, psychology and storytelling, ultimately, is how they both l=
ink.</p></div>
